-- Reliance Industries, Bharti Airtel, Shopper's Stop: India Equity Preview
-- Vipin V. Nair
-- 2010-06-23T02:47:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/reliance-industries-bharti-airtel-shopper-s-stop-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
fell 126.86, or 0.7 percent, to 17,749.69. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange lost 0.7 percent to
5,316.55. The BSE 200 Index retreated 0.5 percent to 2,240.62.
 SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index  futures for June delivery fell 0.6
percent to 5,294 at 10:28 a.m. in Singapore today.  
 Bharti Airtel Ltd.  (BHARTI IN): India’s largest wireless
carrier, which completed a $9 billion purchase of Mobile
Telecommunications Co.’s African assets earlier this month,
plans to invest $100 million in Malawi over the next three years,
said  Manoj Kohli , chief executive officer for the company’s
Africa division. Bharti fell 1.1 percent to 262 rupees.  
 Murli Industries Ltd.  (MRLI IN): Lafarge SA,
HeidelbergCement AG, CRH Plc and Italcementi SpA are among four
global cement companies that have expressed interest in buying
Murli Industries, the Business Standard newspaper reported,
citing two officials it didn’t identify. Murli, a paper and
animal feed maker, fell 1.7 percent to 95.3 rupees.  
 NMDC Ltd.  (NMDC IN): The state-run iron ore producer will
decide by month-end on the prices at which it will sell the raw
material to customers, the Press Trust of India reported, citing
Chairman  Rana Som . The shares fell 0.8 percent to 264.9 rupees.  
 Patel Engineering Ltd.  (PEC IN): The construction company
that counts power producers including NTPC Ltd. as customers
plans to raise about 12 billion rupees ($260 million) selling as
much as 30 percent of its energy unit within a year, Managing
Director  Rupen Patel  said. The stock dropped 1.6 percent to
419.95 rupees.  
 Piramal Healthcare Ltd.  (PIHC IN): The company will pay a
cash bonus to more than 8,000 employees after selling its
formulations business to U.S. drugmaker Abbott Laboratories, the
Economic Times newspaper reported, citing an e-mail sent by
chairman  Ajay Piramal  to the staff. Piramal, a manufacturer of
drugs and glass containers, gained 0.2 percent to 491.7 rupees.  
 Reliance Communications Ltd.  (RCOM IN): The company is in
talks to sell a 26 percent stake to Paris-based Vivendi SA, the
Economic Times newspaper reported, citing an official it didn’t
identify. Reliance Communications, India’s second-largest
wireless carrier, fell 0.5 percent to 186.05 rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd.  (RIL IN): India’s most valuable
company may spend more than $3 billion over the next four to
five years to build capacity for entering the fertilizer
business, Reuters reported, citing a person it didn’t identify.
 Manoj Warrier , a spokesman for Reliance, declined to comment.
Reliance fell 0.2 percent to 1,063.8 rupees.  
 Shopper’s Stop Ltd.  (SHOP IN): India’s second-largest
publicly traded retailer may raise as much as 2 billion rupees
from a sale of shares to large investors to gain a controlling
stake in a local supermarket chain, Chief Executive Officer
 Govind Shrikhande  said in an interview. The shares gained 1.3
percent to 479 rupees.  
